properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: 5 to 15 centimetres of snowfall accumulation today. Strong arctic outflow winds from the Fraser Valley are colliding with the southern Gulf Islands and southeastern Vancouver Island, producing bands of heavy snow. Accumulations will be variable and range from 5 to 15 cm. More flurries with localized accumulations are expected again tonight and Tuesday. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-14T05:55:55-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall and strong winds possible beginning on Thursday Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm or possibly higher. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h or higher. Maximum surge: 50 cm or higher. Wave Heights: 5 metres or higher. High Tide: After midnight Friday and again after noon on Friday. Locations: Prince Edward Island. Time span: Thursday morning into Friday afternoon. Remarks: an intensifying low pressure system approaching from New England will move to lie near southwestern Nova Scotia on Thursday and will skirt the Atlantic coast before heading away on Friday. This may give significant snowfall amounts to most of the province. Winds will possibly reach or exceed warning criteria, especially over eastern regions Thursday night into Friday. High waves and storm surge will affect the southern Gulf of St. Lawrence on Friday. This combined with a run of spring tides may cause flooding and overwash on north facing shorelines of the province, especially in the east. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-14T12:13:07-00:00

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow this morning. A low pressure system over southern BC will continue to spread snow over the region this morning. As well, an arctic front has arrived with strong gusty winds resulting in dropping temperatures. The combination of falling snow with very strong winds will result in blowing snow and poor visibility. Visibility will improve through the morning as snow tapers off and winds ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A multi-day episode of very cold wind chills continues. Bitterly cold arctic air will remain entrenched over the area for several days. Occasional light winds will give wind chill values down to minus 45. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong outflow winds and cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. An arctic front pushed out onto the south coast last night bringing the coldest air so far this winter. Cold arctic air will continue to funnel out of the mainland inlets and valleys today producing northeast winds of 40 to 60 km/h with gusts as high as 80 km/h. The strong winds combined with cold temperatures will generate wind chill values of -20 or lower. Temperatures and winds will start to moderate after mid-week. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong outflow winds and cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. An arctic front pushed out onto the south coast last night bringing the coldest air so far this winter. Cold arctic air will continue to funnel out of the mainland inlets and valleys today producing northeast winds of 40 to 60 km/h with gusts as high as 80 km/h. The strong winds combined with cold temperatures will generate wind chill values of -20 or lower. Temperatures and winds will start to moderate after mid-week. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong outflow winds and severely cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. An arctic ridge of high pressure will remain over the BC interior over the next few days. This system will continue to produce very strong outflow winds, frigid temperatures, and wind chill values of minus 20 and below through the week. ### Frostbite and hypothermia can occur within minutes if adequate precautions are not taken when outdoors. Arctic outflow warnings are issued when bitterly cold air flows from the interior to coastal communities and the outflow winds create wind chill values of -20 or less for 6 hours or more. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
